// The replay-provider test fixture: entries driving `replay.exponential` / `replay.forever` /
// `replay.immediate` end to end over their real compiled IR (the runtime suite loads this module's build
// output — see `test/replay-providers.test.ts`, which also documents how to regenerate `ir.json`). The
// `probe` external is an in-process FFI the tests script to fail N times (a typed throw or a panic) then
// succeed. Each entry pairs a `replay` MECHANISM with a user CONVERTER that turns the probe's failures into
// `replay.interrupted` — the split the redesign is about.

@"The typed error the probe raises while it is still failing."
data probe_failed(attempt: integer)

@"The scripted external under replay: the test's in-process FFI handler decides, per call, whether to throw
`probe_failed` (typed), panic (a plain JS error), or return a value. An FFI throw payload arrives as a bare
structural record (the wire decoder tags nothing), so `probe` below re-raises it as a nominally-tagged
`probe_failed` — exactly what a throw raised from Katari already is, so the converters below stay canonical."
external agent probe_source(kind: string) -> string with prelude.throw[probe_failed]

@"Re-tag the FFI throw as a nominal `probe_failed` (a Katari-constructed value), so a converter can pass the
error straight to its own escalation / `replay.interrupted` — as it would for any throw raised in Katari —
without the escalation boundary rejecting an untagged record. A panic proxies through untouched."
agent probe(kind: string) -> string with prelude.throw[probe_failed] | io {
  use handler {
    request prelude.throw(error: probe_failed) -> never {
      prelude.throw(error = probe_failed(attempt = error.attempt))
    }
  }
  probe_source(kind = kind)
}

@"The converter's OWN failure sum for the both-channels case — a typed `throw` folds to `threw`, a `panic`
to `crashed`. Declared locally (not by `replay`): a converter brings its own `F`; the mechanism never sees
these constructors, only the `interrupted[threw | crashed]` they settle to."
data threw(attempt: integer)
data crashed(message: string)

@"Entry (a): `replay.forever` over a converter that folds BOTH channels — a typed `throw` AND a `panic` —
into `replay.interrupted`, using the converter's OWN two-constructor sum. Failures back off through durable
sleeps (the test drives a ManualClock); when the probe finally succeeds, the value escapes the loop and
returns. Proves the converter can opt into retrying panics, explicitly, in source."
agent forever_main() -> string with io {
  use replay.forever(initial_delay_milliseconds = 5.0, factor = 2.0, max_delay_milliseconds = 20.0)
  use handler {
    request prelude.throw(error: probe_failed) -> never {
      replay.interrupted(failure = threw(attempt = error.attempt))
    }
    request panic(msg: string) {
      replay.interrupted(failure = crashed(message = msg))
    }
  }
  probe(kind = "forever")
}

@"Entry (b): `replay.exponential` that RECOVERS. The converter retries the typed `probe_failed`; the probe
fails a scripted number of times then succeeds within the budget, so the success value returns."
agent exponential_recover_main() -> string with io | prelude.throw[probe_failed] {
  use replay.exponential(initial_delay_milliseconds = 5.0, factor = 2.0, max_attempts = 5.0)
  use handler {
    request prelude.throw(error: probe_failed) -> never {
      replay.interrupted(failure = error)
    }
  }
  probe(kind = "exponential-recover")
}

@"Entry (c): `replay.exponential` that EXHAUSTS. The probe always fails, so the 2-attempt budget is spent and
the provider re-raises the last failure as a TYPED `throw[probe_failed]`; the outer handler catches it by
payload and returns a string — proof the exhausted failure stays typed and the program can catch it."
agent exponential_exhaust_main() -> string with io {
  use handler {
    request prelude.throw(error: probe_failed) -> never {
      break f"exhausted at attempt ${string.to_string(value = error.attempt)}"
    }
  }
  use replay.exponential(initial_delay_milliseconds = 5.0, factor = 2.0, max_attempts = 2.0)
  use handler {
    request prelude.throw(error: probe_failed) -> never {
      replay.interrupted(failure = error)
    }
  }
  probe(kind = "exponential-exhaust")
}

@"The human-in-the-loop escalation this fixture declares FOR ITSELF — NOT part of `replay`. Unhandled, it
escalates to a durable open question that parks the run until answered, then resolves `null`. The attended /
re-auth loop is `replay.immediate()` plus a converter that performs THIS request (park) and then
`replay.interrupted` (re-run on the answer): escalation is an ordinary capability, not replay machinery."
request needs_reauth(detail: probe_failed) -> null

@"Entry (d): `replay.immediate` + a converter that performs the fixture's OWN `needs_reauth` escalation (NO
application handler) — each failure escalates to a durable open question; answering it re-runs the block, and
the eventual success returns. The attended / re-auth loop, composed from a user-declared escalation."
agent attended_main() -> string with needs_reauth | io {
  use replay.immediate()
  use handler {
    request prelude.throw(error: probe_failed) -> never {
      needs_reauth(detail = error)
      replay.interrupted(failure = error)
    }
  }
  probe(kind = "attended")
}

@"Entry (e): the same composition INTERCEPTED — an application handler above the provider answers
`needs_reauth` with `next null`, so each failure re-runs immediately and nothing escalates."
agent intercepted_main() -> string {
  use handler {
    request needs_reauth(detail: probe_failed) { next null }
  }
  use replay.immediate()
  use handler {
    request prelude.throw(error: probe_failed) -> never {
      needs_reauth(detail = error)
      replay.interrupted(failure = error)
    }
  }
  probe(kind = "intercepted")
}
